<h2 id="orgb775d91">My Hammerspoon config</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-orgb775d91">
<p>
<a href="https://www.hammerspoon.org/">Hammerspoon</a> is a tool for automating OS X tasks. In this post, I'll share <a href="https://github.com/ben-maclaurin/hammerspoon/blob/main/init.lua">my configuration</a>.
</p>

<p>
I actually use two: one personal, one professional. However, I've mapped the keys in a way that preserves my sanity. Currently, the setup serves two purposes (if you place window and application management under the same umbrella):
</p>

<ol class="org-ol">
<li>Window management</li>
<li>Browser actions</li>
</ol>

<p>
For window management, I've modelled the manipulation on <a href="https://www.vim.org/">Vim</a> keybindings:
</p>

<ul class="org-ul">
<li><code>CMD</code> + <code>SHIFT</code> + <code>H</code> = width / 2 and left align</li>
<li><code>CMD</code> + <code>SHIFT</code> + <code>J</code> = height / 2 and bottom align</li>
<li><code>CMD</code> + <code>SHIFT</code> + <code>K</code> = height / 2 and top align</li>
<li><code>CMD</code> + <code>SHIFT</code> + <code>L</code> = width / 2 and right align</li>
</ul>

<p>
The <code>F</code> key, a little less synonymous, maximises windows. Here is the little Lua script for <code>CMD</code> + <code>SHIFT</code> + <code>H</code>:
</p>

<div class="org-src-container">
<pre class="src src-lua">hs.hotkey.bind({"cmd", "shift"}, "H", function()
    local win = hs.window.focusedWindow()
    local f = win:frame()
    local screen = win:screen()
    local max = screen:frame()

    f.x = max.x
    f.h = max.h
    f.w = max.w / 2
    win:setFrame(f)
end)
</pre>
</div>

<p>
Next, application switching. Row one houses the standard application shortcuts for both computers:
</p>

<ul class="org-ul">
<li><code>CMD</code> + <code>SHIFT</code> + <code>NUM 7</code> = Firefox</li>
<li><code>CMD</code> + <code>SHIFT</code> + <code>NUM 8</code> = Emacs</li>
<li><code>CMD</code> + <code>SHIFT</code> + <code>NUM 9</code> = Finder</li>
</ul>

<p>
Row two (custom applications): 
</p>

<table border="2" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="6" rules="groups" frame="hsides">


<colgroup>
<col  class="org-left" />

<col  class="org-left" />

<col  class="org-left" />
</colgroup>
<thead>
<tr>
<th scope="col" class="org-left">Key</th>
<th scope="col" class="org-left">Personal</th>
<th scope="col" class="org-left">Work</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td class="org-left"><code>CMD</code> + <code>SHIFT</code> + <code>NUM 4</code></td>
<td class="org-left">Sublime Text</td>
<td class="org-left">PhpStorm</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td class="org-left"><code>CMD</code> + <code>SHIFT</code> + <code>NUM 5</code></td>
<td class="org-left">Alacritty</td>
<td class="org-left">Figma</td>
</tr>

<tr>
<td class="org-left"><code>CMD</code> + <code>SHIFT</code> + <code>NUM 6</code></td>
<td class="org-left">Spotify</td>
<td class="org-left">Microsoft Teams</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<p>
Even this row maintains a narrative of sorts. <code>4</code> is primary focus (code), <code>5</code> for secondary focus (i.e. checking logs or designs), and <code>6</code> for miscellaneous functions.
</p>

<p>
Finally, the last row, which consists of various browser actions:
</p>

<ul class="org-ul">
<li><code>CMD</code> + <code>SHIFT</code> + <code>NUM 1</code> = open new empty tab</li>
<li><code>CMD</code> + <code>SHIFT</code> + <code>NUM 2</code> = show browsing history</li>
<li><code>CMD</code> + <code>SHIFT</code> + <code>NUM 3</code> = open <a href="http://localhost:3000/">http://localhost:3000/</a></li>
</ul>

<p>
I've published the full config file on <a href="https://github.com/ben-maclaurin/hammerspoon/blob/main/init.lua">GitHub</a>.
</p>

